 the end also needs escaping as `\\/`. So the regex should be `^(www|beta)\\.example\\.com\\/` to anchor it to the start and match the exact structure.\n\nI'll create a Flask endpoint that takes a target URL and validates it against this pattern. The `re.match()` function will check if the URL starts with either `www` or `beta`, followed by `.example.com/`. This will correctly match URLs like `www.example.com/path` or `beta.example.com/anything`, while rejecting `example.com/` or `other.example.com/`. match if the string STARTS with the pattern. This seems reasonable.\n\nBut what if the pattern should match the entire URL? In that case, I might want to use `^(www|beta)\\.example\\.com\\/.*$` to match the entire string starting with that pattern and anything after the slash.\n\nI think for the purpose of this task, matching if the URL starts with the pattern makes sense. So I'll go with:\n\n```python\nfrom flask import Flask, request\nimport re\n\napp = Flask(__name__)\n\n@app.route('/check', methods=['GET', 'POST'])\ndef check_url():\n    target_url = request.args.get('target_url')\n    \n    if target_url is None:\n        return False\n    \n    # Pattern to match (www|beta).example.com/\n    pattern = r'^(www|beta)\\.example\\.com\\/'\n    \n    matches = bool(re.match(pattern, target_url))\n    return matches\n\nif __name__ == '__main__':\n    app.run()\n```\n\nThe route path and endpoint name are flexible based on the requirements, so `/check` works well. I'll keep the implementation straightforward with a GET request handler that extracts the target_url parameter and returns whether it matches the domain pattern. and save it to the file.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":10,"cache_creation_input_tokens":4656,"cache_read_input_tokens":24095,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":4656},"output_tokens":3,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available